    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-02-21T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-02-21T11:00:00-05:00" n="368"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d368">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.5123/2311: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atherton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-02-21T16:00:00+00:00"
                            >February 21, 1935—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 12:22 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>76. Embassy has received various requests, including one from London’s largest
                    retail establishment, inquiring as to truth of press reports published here that
                    United States Treasury is enforcing article 674 of the Income Tax
                        Regulations<note n="6" xml:id="d368fn6">U. S. Treasury Department, Bureau of
                        Internal Revenue, <hi rend="italic">Regulations 77 Relating to the Income
                            Tax Under the Revenue Act of 1982</hi>, p. 214.</note> under which
                    British subjects visiting America for business must pay tax on that portion of
                    their British salaries which accrues while they are in the United States.
                    Business houses point out this raises a serious question in regard to their
                    buyers visiting America and I should appreciate data to enable me to make
                    adequate reply.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Atherton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
